<h2>The Little Boracay Experience</h2>

<p>
Unlike traditional beach resorts, Little Boracay is best known for its natural 
sandbar and floating cottage environment. Visitors reach the sandbar by boat 
from the coastal barangays of Calatagan where floating cottages provide shaded 
spaces for groups enjoying the water and scenery.
</p>

<ul>
<li>Wide tidal sandbars</li>
<li>Floating bamboo cottages</li>
<li>Clear shallow coastal waters</li>
<li>Short boat transfers from Calatagan’s shoreline</li>
<li>Popular swimming and photography destination</li>
</ul>

<p>
Because the sandbar appears depending on tide conditions, every visit offers a 
slightly different view of the coastal landscape.
</p>

<h2>Location and Accessibility</h2>

<p>
Little Boracay is located off the coast of <strong>Calatagan, Batangas</strong>, 
a coastal municipality in southern Luzon known for its beaches, fishing 
communities, and growing tourism sector.
</p>

<p>
Travel time from <strong>Metro Manila</strong> to Calatagan generally ranges 
between three to four hours by car depending on traffic. From the coastal 
barangays, visitors arrange a short boat ride to reach the sandbar and 
floating cottage areas.
</p>

<p>
Several nearby coastal landmarks and beach resorts serve as common jump-off 
points for travelers planning a trip to the Little Boracay sandbar.
</p>

