<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<h3>How do you get to Little Boracay in Calatagan?</h3>
<p>
Travelers typically drive from Metro Manila to Calatagan, Batangas, a journey 
that usually takes three to four hours. From the coastal barangays, local boats 
transport visitors to the Little Boracay sandbar.
</p>

<h3>How far is Little Boracay from CaSoBe or Stilts Beach Resort?</h3>
<p>
Little Boracay is located a short distance from several well-known coastal 
areas of Calatagan. Visitors usually reach the sandbar through a short drive 
to the coast followed by a boat transfer.
</p>

<h3>How far is Little Boracay from the Calatagan town center?</h3>
<p>
The Calatagan Public Market and town center are generally around 
15–25 minutes by car from the coastal jump-off areas used for boat 
transfers to the sandbar.
</p>

<h3>Are floating cottages available at Little Boracay?</h3>
<p>
Yes. Floating bamboo cottages are one of the defining features of the 
Little Boracay sandbar and provide shaded resting areas for groups.
</p>

<h3>Can visitors swim at Little Boracay?</h3>
<p>
Yes. The sandbar is known for its clear and shallow waters which make it 
suitable for swimming and relaxing.
</p>

<h3>Is Little Boracay suitable for day trips?</h3>
<p>
Yes. Many visitors travel to Calatagan specifically for day trips to the 
sandbar before returning to Manila or nearby cities.
</p>

<h3>Are transportation options available in Calatagan?</h3>
<p>
Visitors can arrange private vehicles, taxis, or other transport services 
within Calatagan to reach the coastal jump-off areas.
</p>

<h3>When is the best time to visit Little Boracay?</h3>
<p>
Morning to early afternoon is often the best time to visit when tides are 
lower and the sandbar becomes more visible.
</p>

<h3>Is Little Boracay the same as Boracay Island?</h3>
<p>
No. Little Boracay is a sandbar destination in Calatagan, Batangas. It is 
separate from Boracay Island in Aklan, although the white sand and clear 
waters inspired the nickname.
</p>

